o/images/511b71b7-d68f-4fd5-abf2-106ab3668a2a/essay-hi-w7ry2p.jpg?width=3840&amp;quality=75&amp;format=auto"/><div class="sc-d0d42ecb-6 eUtZv"><div class="sc-d0d42ecb-7 kHSJgS"><p>A hibernating Arctic ground squirrel in Fairbanks, Alaska. Its body temperature can drop as low as 2.9°C. Photo by NPL/Alamy</p></div><span class="font-mono">i</span></div></div><div class="sc-d0d42ecb-3 WFpNr"><div class="sc-d0d42ecb-2 eTnGFb"><h2 class="mt-2.5 mb-6 font-semibold font-serif text-7xl leading-none max-[767px]:text-left max-[767px]:text-black max-[960px]:text-[42px] min-[768px]:mt-11 print:text-4xl">Could humans hibernate?</h2><h1 class="sc-d0d42ecb-4 bXNXzL">Hibernation allows many animals to time-travel from difficult times to plenty. Could humans learn how to do it too?</h1><p class="sc-d0d42ecb-5 lmFFbd">by <!-- -->Vladyslav Vyazovskiy<!-- --> <span class="toggleMobileCreditBtn">+ BIO</span></p></div></div></div><div class="sc-1da62608-3 bxykXS"><small class="sc-1da62608-4 izyiOU"><p>A hibernating Arctic ground squirrel in Fairbanks, Alaska. Its body temperature can drop as low as 2.9°C. Photo by NPL/Alamy</p></small></div></div></div><div class="sc-2f963901-0 dGyqlX"><div class="sc-2f963901-5 cAIYqe"><aside class="sc-2f963901-9 kIjnKO"><div aria-hidden="true" class="rah-static rah-static--height-zero SidebarWrapper" style="height:0;overflow:hidden"><div><div class="sc-2e8621ab-0 dTqQqJ sc-2f963901-6 iFSuyF"><a href="/users/vladyslav-vyazovskiy" class="sc-2e8621ab-1 iTsAjg">Vladyslav Vyazovskiy</a><span class="inline [&amp;_p]:inline"><p>is professor of sleep physiology and tutorial fellow in medicine at the University of Oxford, as well as vice-president of the European Sleep Research Society and a TEDx speaker.</p></span></div><br/><div class="sc-2f963901-8 dqFLeN"><p>Edited by<a href="/users/nigel-warburton" class="sc-2e8621ab-1 iTsAjg">Nigel Warburton</a></p></div></div></div><div class="sc-8abcc030-0 koSWWJ"><span>4,300<!-- --> words</span><span class="sc-8abcc030-1 bKfCkA"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor" stroke="none" width="16" height="16" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M21.303,16.553l1.107,3.783l-3.48-2.322c-0.689,0.234-1.422,0.371-2.193,0.371c-1.041,0-2.024-0.234-2.907-0.642 c2.034-1.697,3.333-4.275,3.333-7.166c0-1.994-0.625-3.836-1.677-5.347c0.406-0.073,0.823-0.117,1.251-0.117 c3.762,0,6.814,2.971,6.814,6.634c0,1.594-0.578,3.057-1.539,4.2L21.303,16.553z M15.255,10.684c0,3.861-3.213,6.99-7.176,6.99 c-0.812,0-1.583-0.144-2.31-0.391l-3.667,2.446l1.166-3.985l-0.744-0.638c-1.013-1.203-1.621-2.743-1.621-4.423 c0-3.858,3.215-6.987,7.176-6.987C12.042,3.696,15.255,6.825,15.255,10.684z"></path></svg><span>14<!-- --> <!-- -->comments</span></span><div class="group z-10 inline-flex cursor-pointer items-center gap-1 sm:hidden"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor" stroke="none" width="17" height="17" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M17 3H7c-1.1 0-1.99.9-1.99 2L5 21l7-3 7 3V5c0-1.1-.9-2-2-2zm0 15l-5-2.18L7 18V5h10v13z"></path></svg><span class="flex-shrink-0 font-sans">Save</span></div></div><br/><div class="mx-0 my-5 [grid-area:syndication] print:hidden max-sm:hidden"><a class="inline-flex bg-grey-light-bg p-5 text-center font-mono text-grey-mid text-xs leading-relaxed tracking-widest duration-200 hover:bg-black hover:text-white" href="/syndication?article_slug=how-animals-learned-to-hibernate-and-why-we-cant-do-it-yet&amp;article_name=Could humans hibernate?&amp;author=Vladyslav Vyazovskiy&amp;date=18 November 2024">SYNDICATE THIS <!-- -->ESSAY</a></div><div class="sc-c3e98e6e-0 iontxq sc-2f963901-10 kVaaOI"><div class="sc-c3e98e6e-0 iontxq"><div><br/></div><div class="sc-85a52c0f-0 geqzbm font-sans"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor" stroke="none" width="24" height="24" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" aria-hidde